english:
  title: A Sacrificial Ode to Mister Lin
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I speak to your noble spirit—a hermit of unsullied virtue, a minor official of rare brilliance. Your prose flowed like moonlight through a canyon; your poetry rose like the spine of mountains themselves. The eight instruments of harmony overflowed within you, colors scattering between them like auspicious unicorn and phoenix—rare visitors that appear only when heaven wills it, impossible to find again.

    Once you walked among the wealthy and powerful, where gold accumulated like a mountain spring. It seemed the great families of old competed for your favor, yet the broad highway of fortune never tempted you to abandon your character for its glitter. When the well ran dry and your livelihood withered, when ten thousand things shattered like broken tiles, you stood unshaken. Though you had nowhere to lay your head and nowhere to turn your steps, you never bent your integrity.

    Then your voice rose and split the very stones—spirits wept at the sound. Your bitter anguish filled the heavens until clouds twisted in knots. Like Liu Tzu you were oppressed, like Song Gong you trembled. Every grimace and groan, every cry and laugh, every right and wrong, every gain and loss poured forth from your brush and tongue, and in that torrent of words—like rivers churning driftwood or metal striking crickets—your strange and forceful speech carved out strange and piercing thoughts.

    The hawk does not soar higher, the steadfast pine does not stand firmer, beauty itself cannot match your brilliance, nor can the swift sail outrun your reach. You commanded the Han and Wei dynasties and wove together Zhuangzi and Qu Yuan. Your words pierce armor; your cunning strikes at invisible targets. Pride in your eight-fold gift kept you from begging a single borrowed couplet—you could gather gold as easily as picking stones.

    Yet fate dealt you another hand. Like a merchant carrying caps to Yue or selling shoes to the footless, you stumbled when the moment demanded sure footing. The jade fell shattered; the moon in the mountain pool cracked. At thirty, in plain white robes, you departed—and with you went the eternal grievance of the cinnamon tree.

    The world murmurs that you held yourself too high, that your words were too sharp, that you bore the arrogance of great men and scorned the common things. But this is merely a speck upon clear water, a hairline crack in white jade—why should it matter? Let others hoard their crimson sashes and boast of long life. The turtle and snake endure, but to what end? Your body may have known poverty, yet your talent rivals the stars themselves. Your days were brief, but your name will outlast mountains and sky.

    We two were close once, gathered in your bright presence like glue and lacquer binding fast. But in an instant, that intimate knowing was gone. Now your singing place sits silent, the scent of your presence fades. Who answers when I sing? Who judges my scattered verses? The wine house of old friends lies distant now; only a neighbor's distant flute cries out in sorrow. I lift my face to heaven and weep—and the tears turn to blood.

    Alas, I set before you wine and offering, a single cup in memory, hoping to glimpse again the shadow of your face, the echo of your voice.
  footnotes:
    - The Eight Instruments (八音) refers to instruments made from eight materials in classical Chinese music; here it symbolizes complete harmony and mastery.
    - Liu Tzu and Song Gong are references to ancient sages who endured hardship while maintaining their principles.
    - The references to Han and Wei dynasties invoke the golden age of Chinese literature and philosophical thought.
    - Zhuangzi and Qu Yuan were great philosophers and poets known for their unconventional brilliance and tragic circumstances.
    - The imagery of jade falling and the moon shattering represents the sudden loss of a brilliant person in their prime.
